Smiling !ZzjSmPEuaY Sun 19 Mar 2023 05:39:20 No.55166608 Report
Quoted By: >>55166625 >>55166768 >>55166774 >>55166814 >>55166856 >>55166972
So I was trying to come up with traditional foods throughout the ages for the wider tribes story going into my "modern settings" and into sci-fi and it posed me a few challenges.

A). Furred anthros make for shit metalworkers
B). Beaks, Muzzles, and Mandibles would make for different food delivery methods
C). Assuming some the "base" animal's dietary preferences carry over.

So, assuming that species diversity is maintained with various populations remaining healthy and somewhat isolated. I think interesting food cultures would develop.

Like for example, since canines would l have difficulty with soups, stews, noodles, and small grains like grits, rice, or raw oats they might have a strong culture of vegetable stuffing and sauce-making. Or might have a unique type of spoon that facilitates the tongue motion for thicker porridge like oatmeal. And since canines prefer savory over all other flavors and a strong aversion to spicy, they may have very mild yet savory foods like Jewish brisket as favorites.

Herons, since they'd have difficulty with thing that require a lot of chewing since they'd get stuck in the ridges of the upper beak allowing them to the "chew" may enjoy more "piecemeal" eating like sushi and dumplings while avoiding crunchy, long things like chicken strips or overly chewy food like octopus.
Since birds like spicy but dislike bitter, they may have a a very spicy, colorful palette but avoid things like coffee, tea, beer, and liquor.

Some anthros like Horses, Cows, and some others are mostly similar to humans in the chewing process (closed lip chewing) but would have radically different flavor preferences.

So, I guess, what is your waifur, and her specie's favorite food, and why? Hell you can make up a dish.

Like for example. "Snow Leopard Smoked Fish"
>Aversion to spicy means little pepper
>Preference to Savory may have it served on bread with lard or butter
>May have orange juice rather than lemon
>Bread is cooked with lard and beet juice

Anonymous Sun 19 Mar 2023 05:49:46 No.55166768 Report
Quoted By: >>55166990
>>55166608
>And since canines prefer savory over all other flavors and a strong aversion to spicy, they may have very mild yet savory foods like Jewish brisket as favorites.
I don't know if it's universal but in my experience dogs generally LOVE sweet stuff, the more sugary the better, to the point where some people have to lock up things like cakes and pies to keep the dog from being tempted beyond all endurance. That aside, one of my assumptions whenever I read a story like this is that if they're capable of speech, their mouths, tongues, and lips must be sufficiently similar to ours that they won't have much trouble with most any kind of food. Likewise, humans are all the same species, and the sheer variety of regional cuisines, and eating methods from table cutlery to chopsticks to eating stew on flatbread, well, it suggests to me that you may be overthinking this just a bit. And I get it, it's fun to think about. But for the sake of plausible background for the story I think you can make the details whatever you want, that you think will make a good story. Even tolerance for extremely spicy, piquant flavors varies enormously from culture to culture and from individual to individual. You have the people who can't abide anything more spicy than Miracle Whip on white bread, and you have the people who crossbreed and hybridize super-hot peppers as a hobby--and they may live in the same town.

Currently I am thinking about foxes a lot, and they tend to be very enthusiastic about chicken, and about eggs. My mother's fried chicken recipe, maybe?
